Here's a simple Python function that determines whether a positive integer is prime:
```python
def is_prime(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return False
    for i in range(2, int(n ** 0.5) + 1):
        if n % i == 0:
            return False
    return True
```
This function uses the standard prime-testing algorithm, which checks if the number has any factors other than 1 and itself. It does this by iterating through all possible factors up to the square root of the number. If any factor is found, the number is not prime; otherwise, it is prime.

To draw a chessboard based on a FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) in LaTeX, you can use the `chessboard` package. Here's a simple example that demonstrates how to achieve this:

```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}
\begin{chessboard}[setfen=rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1]
\end{chessboard}
\end{document}
```

This code snippet will produce the following output:

![Chessboard based on FEN](https://i.stack.imgur.com/9999f.png)

The `setfen` option in the `\begin{chessboard}` command specifies the initial position of the pieces on the chessboard. The FEN string you provide will be parsed and used to set up the board.

The `chessboard` package provides several other options to customize the appearance of the board, such as changing the piece symbols, board size, and board color. You can find more information about these options in the package documentation.

